## Why This Is Asked
Tests understanding of multi-account setups and provider aliasing in modules. It also checks proper targeting and drift-free validation.

## Key Concepts
- Terraform providers and aliases
- Module-level provider configuration
- For_each environment handling
- Plan vs apply drift checks

## Code Example
```hcl
provider "aws" {
  alias = "dev"
  # credentials for dev account
}

provider "aws" {
  alias = "prod"
  # credentials for prod account
}

module "storage" {
  for_each = var.environments
  source   = "./modules/storage"
  providers = {
    aws = aws.dev
    aws.prod = aws.prod
  }
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
Tests understanding of multi-region AWS deployments using Terraform provider aliases and proper resource binding to specific providers.

## Key Concepts
- Terraform provider aliases for multiple AWS regions
- Resource addressing with provider assignments
- Cross-region planning and deployment validation

## Code Example
```hcl
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-1"
}

provider "aws" {
  alias  = "west"
  region = "us-west-2"
}

resource "aws_vpc" "east_vpc" {
  cidr_block = "10.0.0.0/16"
}

resource "aws_nat_gateway" "west_nat" {
  provider     = aws.west
  allocation_id = aws_eip.nat_eip.id
  subnet_id    = aws_subnet.west_subnet.id
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
Tests understanding of provider aliases and per-environment module instantiation in Terraform.

## Key Concepts
- Provider aliases and module-level provider mappings
- For_each environment deployment and target verification
- Safe plan/apply separation per environment

## Code Example
```javascript
provider "aws" {
  alias = \"dev\"
  region = \"us-west-2\"
}
provider "aws" {
  alias = \"prod\"
  region = \"us-east-1\"
}
variable \"environments\" { type = \"map(string)\"; default = { prod = \"prod\"; staging = \"staging\" } }

module \"vpc\" {
  for_each = var.environments
  source   = \"./modules/vpc\"
  providers = {
    aws = each.key == \"prod\" ? aws.prod : aws.dev
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test rollback if prod plan uses the wrong alias?
- How can you enforce alias usage at plan time to prevent mix-ups?

## Why This Is Asked

This question tests multi-account Terraform patterns: provider aliases, cross-account data sources, and deterministic apply order.

## Key Concepts

- Aliased providers
- Cross-account data sources
- Data referencing across providers
- depends_on for ordering
- Credentials management via profiles and assume_role

## Code Example

```hcl
provider "aws" {
  alias   = "prod"
  region  = "us-east-1"
  profile = "prod"
}
provider "aws" {
  alias   = "audit"
  region  = "us-east-1"
  profile = "audit"
}

data "aws_caller_identity" "prod" {
  provider = aws.prod
}

data "aws_s3_bucket" "prod_bucket" {
  provider = aws.prod
  bucket   = "my-prod-bucket"
}

data "aws_iam_policy_document" "audit" {
  provider = aws.audit
  statement {
    actions   = ["s3:GetObject"]
    resources = ["${data.aws_s3_bucket.prod_bucket.arn}/*"]
    principals {
      type        = "AWS"
      identifiers = ["arn:aws:iam::${data.aws_caller_identity.prod.account_id}:root"]
    }
  }
}

resource "aws_s3_bucket" "audit_bucket" {
  provider = aws.audit
  bucket   = "audit-bucket"
}

resource "aws_iam_policy" "audit_policy" {
  provider = aws.audit
  name     = "CrossAccountGetObject"
  policy   = data.aws_iam_policy_document.audit.json
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you rotate credentials for the aliased providers safely?
- How would you test this cross-account permission in a CI workflow?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests practical control of network addressing across environments, Terraform input validation, and CI gating to prevent risk without applying changes.

## Key Concepts
- CIDR overlap validation in Terraform
- Module input validation
- CI gates using plan
- Multi-env network design

## Code Example
```terraform
variable "environment_cidrs" {
  type = map(string)
  validation {
    condition = alltrue([
      for env, cidr in var.environment_cidrs : cidr != "" && !contains(var.allocated_cidrs, cidr)
    ])
    error_message = "CIDR overlaps with allocated CIDRs or is empty"
  }
}
variable "allocated_cidrs" {
  type = set(string)
  description = "CIDRs already allocated to prod/staging"
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you extend this to handle dynamic CIDR allocation across environments?
- How would you handle updates to the allocated CIDR store without causing plan drift?
